<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-05-17T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-05-17T04:00:00-05:00" n="1102" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1102">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">700.0011 Pacific/4: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-05-17T18:00:00+09:00">May 17, 1937—6
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received May 17—9:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>130. The Foreign Office spokesman today told newspapermen that although
                            the Foreign Office lacks official information about the reported speech
                            of last week in London by Premier Lyons of Australia with regard to a
                            nonaggression pact for nations around the Pacific, as a fundamental idea
                            Japan has no objection to participation. The spokesman added that
                            Japan’s attitude cannot be stated until details of the proposal are
                            learned.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
